<h2>Challenges</h2>

<p>One of the things I quickly learned in the project was how complex a Care Plan can be. On one end, there are things like "5 steps to combat sunburn". One the other, it could be treating a 65 year old woman with hypertension and cancer history, treating type 2 diabetes.</p>

<p>In order to keep the project within reasonable scope, we decided to focus on a small set of medical conditions for the beta launch. We would receive feedback from the beta and iteratively add support more conditions.</p>

<h2>Scoping</h2>

<p>We focused on just 4 medical conditions:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Pregnancy</li>
  <li>HIV</li>
  <li>Type 2 diabetes</li>
  <li>Hypertention</li>
</ul>

<p>We also worked with a <b>small group of patients</b> part of a similar medical program with our partner care provider who were able to provide quick feedback. In addition to receiving feedback from the users, we collaborated closely with experts in our doctor network.</p>

<h2>Discovery</h2>

<h4>Care Plan language</h4>
<p>Care Plans have 2 components:</p>
<ul>
  <li><b>Trigger</b> - defines "when" a patient need to take action(s)</li>
  <li><b>Action</b> - defines "what" a patient needs to do</li>
</ul>

<p>Triggers can be <b>time</b> or <b>event</b> based.</p>
<p>Time-based example:<br>
[WHEN] A month after enrolling in the Care Plan,<br>
[WHAT] The patient must schedule a visit with their primary care provider.</p>
<p>Event-based example:<br>
[WHEN] In the case of feet swelling<br>
[WHAT] The patient must schedule a visit with a Podiatrist.</p>

