<p>One of the first things I learned as I started was to assume little and to ask a lot. My assumption in the targeted user group was wrong. When I interviewed the actual user group, they provided lots of information that directly affected the design. For example, because of the tight and hectic schedules of doctors and the software they were already used to, they preferred UI elements to be bigger, bolder, and <b>more obvious</b>. They loved color-coding and highlighted clickable areas. They wanted the software to just work, and not be another tool they have to <i>learn</i>.</p>

